  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Human Rights and Business</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The activity is a two year programme primarily focused on integrating human rights into the curricula of business students in the Ghana Institute of Public Administration (GIMPA) to raise awareness among students (bachelors and masters level) and business professionals (employers &lt;(&gt;&amp;&lt;)&gt; employees) about human rights law, and the rights and obligations imposed by those laws in a business context. Specifically the integrated curricula would encapsulate among others, topics relating to; freedom of expression and internet freedom at the workplace, LGBTI equal rights at the workplace,  freedom of religion and belief of workers,  equal rights for women at the world of work, the right to defend impunity and work related injustices, due process and  accountability at the world of work. This activity has become necessary because there is generally lack of awareness of laws that exist to safeguard fundamental human rights in the workplace against the backdrop of wanton abuse of human rights at work places in Ghana. More so, all educational institutions (except law faculties) in Ghana do not have in-depth, specific, comprehensive and well integrated human rights in business curricula designed to prepare students adequately for the world of work.  This denies students who eventually become; workers, managers and business leaders/entrepreneurs to promote, demand and exact human rights practices in the business environment/world of work. The activity would involve integrating and teaching human rights in business modules  in graduate and post graduate programmes of the university. It would also involve institutionalizing and running short course modules on human rights for employers and employees. Again seminars on Human Rights in Business would be organized with participants from the academia and the world of work.</narrative>
  </description>
